ake."%0a%3c "James should be working on it is who should be working on it." (Example of reversal)%0a%3c "We should do it my way is how we should do it." (Example of reversal)%0a%3c %0a%3c Repetition clefts occur more frequently in speech than in writing. They typically called ‘marginal,’ meaning they are somewhere between strictly grammatical and ungrammatical. Interestingly, they do not correlate with any demographical features but are widespread in several different dialects.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.researchgate.net/publication/268001311_The_Frozenness_of_Pseudoclefts_-_Towards_an_Inequality-based_Syntax%0a%3c https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/repetition-clefts%0a%3c https://www.grammaring.com/pseudo-cleft-sentences%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: B:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
